<subSubSection id="825E490D2EFD38CE6AC487A83A55CEE0" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="76BC25E1438E3F1E58A31A4EB76C0666" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3BA8C84AA9F9E65C4728870C87AE5DA0" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis id="83C0A1225C4F28CDBA85548E5E82DF75" bold="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
(
<figureCitation id="48C34EF5D3695D610F23E66FFA4284AF" captionStart="Figure 15" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figure 15. Distribution of Lepidium aegrum, Lepidium amissum, Lepidium castellanum (Kermadec Islands only), Lepidium banksii, and Lepidium crassum." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10753" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Endemic. New Zealand, North Island, where it was recorded from 'between Manukau Heads and 
<normalizedToken id="1ED5329D63F7D94CA9812E5CE24D336F" originalValue="Karekare’">Karekare'</normalizedToken>
(
<bibRefCitation id="3E33567162D022547495B3A05D03515F" author="Cheeseman, TF" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" refId="B11" refString="Cheeseman, TF, 1906. Manual of the New Zealand flora. Government Printer, Wellington." title="Manual of the New Zealand flora. Government Printer, Wellington." year="1906">Cheeseman 1906</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="589330D57ABAAB20FFCFFE28F014409B" author="Cheeseman, TF" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" refId="B12" refString="Cheeseman, TF, 1925. Manual of the New Zealand flora. 2nd ed. Government Printer, Wellington." title="Manual of the New Zealand flora. 2 nd ed. Government Printer, Wellington." year="1925">1925</bibRefCitation>
), not 
<pageBreakToken id="48983FF2E9DAB54AF925CA714601A1F5" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" start="start">the</pageBreakToken>
<normalizedToken id="BCD10A7E33F76BC17D9BA93C8C6B9778" originalValue="‘Titirangi’">'Titirangi'</normalizedToken>
noted by 
<bibRefCitation id="860DDE7DEF0580EECAECAF8C094BF904" author="Kirk, T" journalOrPublisher="New Zealand Journal of Botany" pageId="114" pageNumber="115" refId="B60" refString="Kirk, T, 1899. The Student's Flora of New Zealand. Government Printer, Wellington." title="The Student's Flora of New Zealand. Government Printer, Wellington." year="1899">Kirk (1899)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName id="26D86130389AB1828045DE663825D210" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amissum">
<emphasis id="8A5812CC28F42B22FDD51D0A882F44D1" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Lepidium amissum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was last collected from the west Auckland coastline in 1917 and is presumed to be extinct.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7782DA8C38DDB78C0E48F71C7DEC606D" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="recognition">
<paragraph id="CE7ACAEE04A8DF9AEFEC6DDB01597062" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Recognition.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="19985B28A2A52A9E6C174081D634044A" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<taxonomicName id="22644EC43274C7D4150AB4B6576F7D2F" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amissum">
<emphasis id="AF050FC1140F5AF03E2C85C5CDD8FCB5" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Lepidium amissum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had previously been included in 
<taxonomicName id="91C5D4273EEE1EE50891223C3D2D747E" authorityName="Kirk, Trans. et Proc. New Zealand Inst. 24, 423" authorityYear="1892" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obtusatum">
<emphasis id="C047FD323E536883A24325856EEE73FE" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Lepidium obtusatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, perhaps because the species have no obvious floral differences and both have deeply notched and winged silicles with tapering bases. However, from 
<taxonomicName id="B788A2DFD63F036F258B96FDB1BDC793" authorityName="Kirk, Trans. et Proc. New Zealand Inst. 24, 423" authorityYear="1892" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obtusatum">
<emphasis id="568244F959B8733B88E2494535CE912D" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Lepidium obtusatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="9A47DA2281C6007039459E9924AF4445" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amissum">
<emphasis id="11A5CFE09978E1D4937126AD3F81DD7A" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Lepidium amissum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs by the non-rhizomatous, suberect growth habit; arching, sparingly leafy stems (
<figureCitation id="4E06CDD733288F2E2D124612D632B448" captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figure 16. Holotype of Lepidium amissum de Lange et Heenan." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10754" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
); long persistent, deeply, and sharply incised rosette and lower stem leaves (
<figureCitation id="0C457F5B9169E49818C5F7AE7F35B76F" captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figure 17. Basal stem leaves of Lepidium amissum. AK 4473" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10755" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Figs 17</figureCitation>
<figureCitation id="7FA938435C3921E1AE6F7D1508E7479E" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Basal stem leaf of Lepidium amissum. AK 4473." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10756" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">, 18</figureCitation>
); upper stem leaves which are lanceolate, narrowly oblanceolate, to narrowly obdeltoid and mostly prominently toothed, with up to 6 pairs of deeply incised teeth, and with a truncate apex bearing 3-4 prominent teeth. The inflorescences of 
<taxonomicName id="2103BB77F0A2C02E49450FB1DA9AF235" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amissum">
<emphasis id="F75201721F8B446FDD59650D776BFA93" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Lepidium amissum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are larger, only sparsely leafy when mature, and without associated vegetative stems (
<figureCitation id="A8B655BF3EA50F4D9D607FED8381ED93" captionStart="Figure 19" captionStartId="F19" captionText="Figure 19. Upper-stem leaves and inflorescences of Lepidium amissum. AK 4473." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10757" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
). The silicles are smaller than those of 
<taxonomicName id="261683BB018694253A67B0092DCE8976" authorityName="Kirk, Trans. et Proc. New Zealand Inst. 24, 423" authorityYear="1892" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obtusatum">
<emphasis id="1E423C6853AADD4134BB7CC9A9B36413" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Lepidium obtusatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="E61E6F975BDC1CCCD375BB22B0EB76C3" captionStart="Figure 20" captionStartId="F20" captionText="Figure 20. Mature silicle of Lepidium amissum. AK 4473. Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10758" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D46AB45F4F34932A1D7CAEB3CABD7946" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="892636265B1689EACC6EEBCFC294B61B" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<pageBreakToken id="F9EE1A36B3703940FACE39E4D1A8E608" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" start="start">Ecology</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="909CB62893C49E654F9DC7159F3CEA98" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
Little is known about the habitat preferences and ecology of 
<taxonomicName id="75C76326AC3DD746FF4D48C688BD324E" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amissum">
<emphasis id="E41847299CE42246F58CDC33599162B9" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Lepidium amissum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, beyond that it grew on sea cliffs (
<bibRefCitation id="BA97C4F9B9EFBF33BD07EECA7AC62571" author="Cheeseman, TF" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" refId="B11" refString="Cheeseman, TF, 1906. Manual of the New Zealand flora. Government Printer, Wellington." title="Manual of the New Zealand flora. Government Printer, Wellington." year="1906">Cheeseman 1906</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="E2D76BD1F13FD3BB374E610AF2B2756B" author="Cheeseman, TF" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" refId="B12" refString="Cheeseman, TF, 1925. Manual of the New Zealand flora. 2nd ed. Government Printer, Wellington." title="Manual of the New Zealand flora. 2 nd ed. Government Printer, Wellington." year="1925">1925</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="484F056F6515BD087C213A49965CFA87" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="conservation status">
<paragraph id="264441F078983B53AAD8AE9C71434350" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Conservation Status.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4360FF43521B4992B3F4DBA1C49D9EDD" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<taxonomicName id="DD2A0CB0ECB953055AC351E0EB4F6E2D" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amissum">
<emphasis id="81B1317D74EBE88D923F87814769653D" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Lepidium amissum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is considered to be extinct. There have been repeated unsuccessful surveys for this species over the last fifty years by various botanists. Aside from the type the species is known from only one collection made in 1917. This collection and the type came from an ill defined area of coastline stretching for some 6 km from the Manukau Heads to Karekare. Today this coastline is protected within the Centennial Park, Waitakere Ranges. However, during the period when this species was gathered, all of the coastline was being modified as a result of kauri (
<taxonomicName id="A35BE0C619FF1F68D831D9F53CE69277" class="Hexapoda" family="Braconidae" genus="Agathis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis id="3D5B3BF64B9C14B9E161D52E3580B390" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Agathis australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(D.Don) Lindl.) logging (see 
<bibRefCitation id="A902ACE43DE382313FE089226953FA98" author="Harvey, B" journalOrPublisher="New Zealand Journal of Botany" pageId="114" pageNumber="115" refId="B48" refString="Harvey, B, 2001. Whatipu: the story of Whatipu and early Huia. Dunmore Press Ltd., Palmerston North." title="Whatipu: the story of Whatipu and early Huia. Dunmore Press Ltd., Palmerston North." year="2001">Harvey 2001</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="FAFEA8634D54D8D8B7BA7D6021932181" author="Harvey, B" editor="Harvey, B" journalOrPublisher=", New Lynn" pageId="114" pageNumber="115" pagination="221 - 233" refId="B49" refString="Harvey, B, 2006. The Manukau shore'. In: Harvey, B, Harvey, T, Eds., Waitakere Ranges - Ranges of Inspiration, The Waitakere Ranges Protection Society Inc., New Lynn: 221 - 233" title="The Manukau shore'" volumeTitle="Waitakere Ranges - Ranges of Inspiration, The Waitakere Ranges Protection Society Inc." year="2006">2006</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="735D1C97B5FBE1E3BC1BAEF8B076FBFE" author="MacDonald, F" journalOrPublisher="New Zealand Journal of Botany" pageId="115" pageNumber="116" refId="B62" refString="MacDonald, F, Kerr, R, 2009. West: the history of Waitakere. Random House, Auckland." title="West: the history of Waitakere. Random House, Auckland." year="2009">MacDonald and Kerr 2009</bibRefCitation>
), and this may have contributed to its eventual extirpation. It does seem that 
<taxonomicName id="010DD614897FF13071EC60E74E19D9C2" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amissum">
<emphasis id="BE8FABF0221CEB972A6B78E1CB40D564" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Lepidium amissum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was already uncommon at the time of its discovery and it is possible that the gatherings made by Thomas Cheeseman where sufficient to cause its extinction as they are copious and comprise many stems.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
